  "story": {
    "problem": "HTTPX - A next-generation HTTP client for Python.\n\n    \n\n    \n\nHTTPX is a fully featured HTTP client library for Python 3. It includes **an integrated command line client**, has support for both **HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2**, and provides both **sync and async APIs**.\n\n---\n\nInstall HTTPX using pip:\n\n``shell\n$ pip install httpx\n`\n\nNow, let's get started:\n\n`pycon\n>>> import httpx\n>>> r = httpx.get('https://www.example.org/')\n>>> r\n\n>>> r.status_code\n200\n>>> r.headers['content-type']\n'text/html;…",
    "mental_model": "HTTPX builds on the well-established usability of requests, and gives you:\n\n* A broadly requests-compatible API.\n* An integrated command-line client.\n* HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 support.\n* Standard synchronous interface, but with async support if you need it.\n* Ability to make requests directly to WSGI applications or ASGI applications.\n* Strict timeouts everywhere.\n* Fully type annotated.\n* 100% test…",
    "when_to_use": "Use httpx when you need the next generation http client.",
    "when_not_to_use": "",
    "alternatives": []
  },
